         <div type="translation">
            <p> [From Probalinthos.] Elpines, son of Elpinicus, from Probalinthus. Eunicus, son of Elpinicus, from Probalinthus.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The edition follows Camp (1996). The stele was named the “Marathon Stone” based on
                    its provenance.  The first line of text above the rosettes reported by previous editors is no longer
                    visible. The next three lines below the rosettes were inscribed in large deep lettering that suggests a dating near the middle of the fourth century
                    BCE. The last three lines commemorating the dedicatee’s brother who died later were added subsequently. They are less deeply carved and so were
                    not read initially when the stele was found.</p>
         </div>
